3. In senatu princeps] i.e. princeps senatus. The man of highest standing among the censorii, those who had been censore, was appointed princeps of the senate, and his opinion was first asked on any question in debate. He continued prin- ceps during his lifetime. After the year B.c. 210, the censors appointed the most worthy of the censorii. See in Liv. xxvii. 11 the story of the appointment of Q. Fabius Maximus.
